<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=10546325533945></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f10546325533945><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=1&mid=10546325533945>RE: A more challenging Question of the Day</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=1&mid=10546325533945#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=103498><span id=Sage>kdsktan</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>120 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Jun 3rd 6:09 AM 2003</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>If you want to get anywhere you a great guild can be invaluable.<br><br>First off, your best bet to research would be your local server ezboard. Just ask around for the URL. I know on my server, emarr, we maintain a page with links to all the current servers on the guild, so this makes it very very easy to look up guilds and find out what they are about.<br><br>However, just reading a webpage can only tell you so much. My advice would be this. Whenever you join pick-up groups now, take a look at the guild tags of the players you are grouped with. If you start to see that a certain guild always has players that you think are fun/skilled etc, then that may point you in the right direction. <br><br>Dont be afraid to ask questions. These are the important things you should know about a guild before you make any decision:-<br><br>a. Numbers - too many is not good imo. Just shows a lack of skill, v hard to control. Together with numbers - also look at balance. A guild should have a even distribution of casters, melee etc. Core raid classes should also be present in sufficient numbers - i.e a few clerics, enchanters, shamans, warriors, mages bards etc. also wizards/druids for tp duties. <br><br>b. Loot distribution - how is loot distributed. My preference would be for a guild that ran a DKP or officer appointed system. I find NBG roll isnt always the best as it can award stuff to casual participants over those who put a lot of time in.<br><br>c. membership process - this to me is the most important. The more hoops you ahve to go through for probation, the more chance it is you will find yourself in a good guild. This is because you simply cant assess the quality of people on the basis of an application. If its a guild that will jsut invite you on the strength of that, then id walk away. Ideally you would need to participatei n a few groups/raids so you can get to know each other. Then get invited to probation and have a period of assessment.<br><br>Finally, playtimes. TO get the most from the guild and to ensure you can contribute to your potential, your playtimes have to match. So check what days they raid and make sure it meets your playtimes. Also, exp grouping is also helpful if your in a guild, so whenever your own - do a &quot;who all&quot; and check how many of the guild are online. If for example its a 50 strong guild but only 5-10 are online at the times that you play, then it may not necessarily be the best match.<br><br>GOod luck in your search. If you find a good guild, it really can increase your enjoyment of the game immensely. <br><br>Gulug<br>63 Warlord<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
